'''Hastatic order''' is a fundamental way of breaking double [[T-symmetry|"time-reversal" symmetry]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Francis|first1=Matthew|title=Double time-reversal asymmetry could explain weird material behavior|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2013/01/double-time-reversal-asymmetry-could-explain-weird-material-behavior/|publisher=Ars Technica|accessdate=20 August 2015}}</ref> It is present in the [[heavy-fermion]] compound [[URu2Si2|URu<sub>2</sub>Si<sub>2</sub>]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/2/18/4002550/scientists-find-weird-new-property-of-matter-that-breaks-all-the-rules|title=Scientists find weird new property of matter that breaks all the rules|author=Arikia|publisher=Vox Media|work=The Verge}}</ref> This order was dubbed ''hastatic'' from ''hasta'', the Latin word for "spear".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chandra|first1=Premala|last2=Coleman|first2=Piers|last3=Flint|first3=Rebecca|title=Hastatic order in the heavy-fermion compound URu2Si2|journal=Nature|date=January 2013|volume=493|issue=621|pages=621–626|doi=10.1038/nature11820|url=http://www.physics.rutgers.edu/~pchandra/Hastatic_Nature.pdf|accessdate=20 August 2015|bibcode = 2013Natur.493..621C|pmid=23364741}}</ref> Its cycle is twice as complex as [[magnetism]].

==Discovery==

Hastatic order was first reported in January 2013 when the heavy-fermion uranium compound URu<sub>2</sub>Si<sub>2</sub> was cooled to nearly {{convert|-415|F|C}}. It was said to produce extra heat and the heat was the main mystery. After the extra heat was released, particles were arranged at this way, making the hastatic order present on that reaction.

