{{RefImprove|date=June 2018}} {|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- commercial vessels --> | infobox caption = <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text --> | display title = <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup --> }} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image = | Ship image size = | Ship caption = The Isla Bella leaving Jacksonville }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header = | Ship country = [[US]] | Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|US|civil}} | Ship name = ''Isla Bella'' | Ship owner = [[TOTE Maritime]]<ref name=Schuler>{{cite news|last1=Schuler|first1=Mike|title=Introducing ISLA BELLA – World’s First LNG-Powered Containership Launched at NASSCO|url=|accessdate=|publisher=gCaptain|date=19 April 2015}}</ref> | Ship operator = TOTE Services | Ship registry = [[United States]] | Ship route = Jacksonville, Florida to [[Puerto Rico]] | Ship ordered = | Ship builder = [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company]] | Ship original cost = | Ship yard number = | Ship way number = | Ship laid down = | Ship completed = | Ship christened = 18 April 2015<ref name=islamaiden>{{cite web|title=Isla Bella Christening|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DATQXUIgQzM|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> | Ship acquired = | Ship maiden voyage = 18 April 2015<ref name=islamaiden /> | Ship in service = 19 October 2015<ref name=certification>{{cite web|title=Coast Guard certifies El Faro's replacement|url=http://www.news4jax.com/news/coast-guard-certifies-el-faros-replacement/35926164|accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> | Ship out of service = | Ship identification = *[[call sign]]:WTOI *{{IMO Number|9680841}} *{{MMSI|338760000}} | Ship fate = | Ship status = Operational | Ship notes = <ref name=vesseltracker>{{cite web | title=Advanced Masterdata for the Vessel ''Isla Bella'' | url=http://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Isla-Bella-9680841.html | work=VesselTracker | date=2015 | accessdate=20 October 2015}}</ref> }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header = | Header caption = | Ship class = Marlin | Ship type = | Ship tonnage = 36751 [[Gross register tonnage|GRT]] | Ship displacement = | Ship length = 764 feet | Ship beam = 106 feet | Ship height = | Ship draught = | Ship draft = | Ship depth = | Ship decks = | Ship deck clearance = | Ship ramps = | Ship ice class = | Ship sail plan = | Ship power = | Ship propulsion = | Ship speed = | Ship capacity = | Ship crew = | Ship notes = }} |}
'''''Isla Bella''''' and her sister ship ''Perla del Caribe'' are the world's first [[LNG|liquefied natural gas]] (LNG) powered [[container ship]]<nowiki/>s. ''Isla Bella'' is currently used as part of the Florida-Puerto Rico trade, sailing out of Jacksonville, Florida and arriving in San Juan, Puerto Rico on a weekly basis. Both ships were built by [[National Steel and Shipbuilding Company|NASSCO]] for [[TOTE Maritime|TOTE Maritime Puerto Rico]] and replaced the last of the [[SS El Faro|ponce-class]] ships that were previously used for the route. They cost $324 million US dollars to built and each is propelled by a single slow speed engine capable of 25,191 [[KW]] at 104 [[rpm]], which propels the ships at a maximum speed of 22 [[Knot (unit)|knots]].{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
The ''Isla Bella'' has a length of 764 feet and is 106 feet in width. It has a capacity of 3,100 [[Twenty-foot equivalent unit|TEU]] but has the ability to carry 20 foot, 30 foot, 40 foot, 45 foot and 53 foot containers. The ''Isla Bella'' was christened of April 18 before a crowd of 3,400 people. The name ''Isla Bella'' is Spanish for “beautiful island.” The name of the vessel comes from Paola Dominguez as part of a partnership with The Puerto Rico Boys & Girls Club and TOTE.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
== Engine and fuel == ''Isla Bella''<nowiki/>'s engine is powered by a single slow speed [[MAN Diesel|MAN B&W 8L70ME-GI]] dual fuel gas engine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://marine.mandieselturbo.com/docs/librariesprovider6/technical-papers/me-gi-dual-fuel-man-b-amp-w-engines433833f0bf5969569b45ff0400499204.pdf?sfvrsn=34|title="ME-GI Dual Fuel MAN B&W Engines A Technical, Operational and Cost-effective Solution for Ships Fuelled by Gas"|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-05}}</ref> This engine operates on a mixture of LNG and [[diesel fuel oil]], the latter of which is used to ignite the natural gas. The engines are designed to run on as little as 3 percent pilot oil. The result is a 97 percent reduction in sulfur oxides and a 98 percent nitrogen oxide reduction in particulate matter coming from the exhausts.<ref name=":0">Miller, Rich (November 9, 2015). [http://www.professionalmariner.com/American-Ship-Review-2016/Isla-Bella/ "Isla Bella"]. ''professionalmariner''. Retrieved 2018-03-26.</ref> To fuel this engine two 900 cubic meter cryogenic tanks are located aft of the house.The combined weight of these two tanks is 760 tons. These eighty-four-foot-long tanks hold a combined total of 475,000 gallons of LNG.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
For the first few years, the ship was refueled from trucks. As of 2018 a dedicated LNG bunker barge and a LNG liquification plant are being built for the ''Isla Bella'' and ''Perla del Caribe''.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
