[[File:NACA-subm-inlet-early-jet.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Artist's concept picture of a submerged inlet for a jet aircraft]] A '''NACA duct''',<ref>Frick, Charles W., et al. NACA ACR No. 5120, ''An Experimental Investigation of NACA Submerged- Duct Entrances''. NACA, November 13, 1945. [https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=906732&id=1&as=false&or=true&qs=Ntt%3DNACA-ACR-5I20%26Ntk%3DReport%2B-%2BPatent%2BNumber%26Ntx%3Dmode%2Bmatchall%26Ns%3DHarvestDate%257c1%26N%3D0 Abstract], [http://naca.central.cranfield.ac.uk/reports/1945/naca-acr-5i20.pdf Full report].</ref> also sometimes called a NACA scoop or NACA inlet, is a common form of low-[[aerodynamic drag|drag]] air inlet design, originally developed by the U.S. [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]] (NACA), the precursor to [[NASA]], in 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://naca.central.cranfield.ac.uk/report.php?NID=2176|title=NACA UK Mirror report description page|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://naca.central.cranfield.ac.uk/|title=MAGiC NACA Archive|publisher=}}</ref>
==Design== Prior submerged inlet experiments showed poor [[pressure recovery]] due to the slow-moving [[boundary layer]] entering the inlet. This design is believed to work because the combination of the gentle ramp angle and the curvature profile of the walls creates counter-rotating [[vortex|vortices]] which deflect the boundary layer away from the inlet and draws in the faster moving air, while avoiding the [[form drag]] and [[flow separation]] that can occur with protruding scoop designs.
==Aircraft applications== [[File:NACA submerged inlets.JPG|right|thumb|300 px|Three intakes on an engine [[cowling]] ]] When properly implemented, a NACA duct allows air to flow into an internal duct, often for cooling purposes, with a minimal disturbance to the flow. The design was originally called a [[submerged inlet]], since it consists of a shallow ramp with curved walls recessed into the exposed surface of a streamlined body, such as an [[fixed-wing aircraft|aircraft]].
This type of flush inlet generally cannot achieve the larger ram pressures and flow volumes of an external design, and so is rarely used for the [[jet engine]] intake application for which it was originally designed, such as the [[North American YF-93]] and [[Short SB.4 Sherpa]]. It is, however, common for piston engine and ventilation intakes.
==Automobile applications== [[File:Ferrari F40 in IMS parking lot.jpg|thumb|right|300 px|Numerous ducts on the [[Ferrari F40]] ]] It is especially favored in [[racing car]] design.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Duct Soup – How A NACA Duct Works|journal=Hot Rod|url=http://www.hotrod.com/articles/naca-duct/}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Race and Rally Car Sourcebook |last=Staniforth |isbn=1-85960-846-9 }} (Practical guidance on designing and building NACA ducts for motor-racing applications)</ref> Famous sports cars featuring prominent NACA ducts include the [[Ferrari F40]], the [[Lamborghini Countach]], the 1971-1973 [[Ford Mustang]], the 1973 [[Pontiac GTO]], [[Porsche 911 GT2]]
